Chapter 2: Literature Review

2.1 Neural Plasticity Models

· Hebbian learning: "Neurons that fire together, wire together." Mathematically, $\Delta w_{ij} = \eta \nu_i \nu_j$. Extensions include the covariance rule and BCM theory, which incorporate sliding thresholds to prevent unbounded growth.
· Spike-Timing Dependent Plasticity (STDP): Weights are modified based on the precise timing of pre- and post-synaptic spikes, with potentiation for pre-before-post and depression for post-before-pre.
· Homeostatic plasticity: Mechanisms that keep total synaptic input to a neuron within a stable range, preventing runaway excitation or silencing.
· Structural plasticity: Models where synapses and neurons can be created or removed. The SynaptoGen model provides a probabilistic framework linking gene expression to synaptic connectivity.
· Self-Motivated Growing Neural Networks (SMGrNN): Uses local activation statistics and weight-update variance to decide neuron insertion/pruning in a fully online, decentralized manner, reducing parameter explosion and improving continual control.

2.2 Evolving and Generative Neural Networks

· NEAT (NeuroEvolution of Augmenting Topologies): Evolves network topology and weights using genetic algorithms, starting from minimal structures and complexifying over generations.
· HyperNEAT: Uses compositional pattern-producing networks to generate large-scale neural structures with regular patterns.
· Capsule Networks: Introduced by Hinton et al., capsules output vectors representing entity properties, with dynamic routing by agreement. This provides a natural representation for part-whole hierarchies and has inspired the vector-based capsules in this work.
· LNDP: Uses Graph Transformer with GRU dynamics for activity- and reward-dependent synaptogenesis/pruning, enabling decentralized differentiation and lifelong adaptation in non-stationary environments.

2.3 Modular and Multi-Agent Systems

· Mixture of Experts: Gating networks route inputs to specialised sub-networks, allowing conditional computation.
· Multi-agent reinforcement learning: Agents learn to coordinate in shared environments, sometimes developing emergent communication protocols.
· Hamiltonian Neural Networks: Incorporate physical principles to learn conservative dynamics, providing inspiration for the energy-based formulation of multi-nuclei systems.
· phMARL: Uses self-attention-based IDA-PBC (interconnection-damping assignment passivity-based control) on port-Hamiltonian multi-robot policies, ensuring energy conservation and distributed stability.

2.4 Resilience and Robustness in Networks

· Graph-theoretic metrics: Redundancy, modularity, centrality quantify structural robustness.
· Percolation theory: Resilience to random vs. targeted attacks.
· Functional resilience: Measuring system performance under perturbation.
· Lesion studies in AI: Simulating damage to evaluate recovery and reorganization, directly inspired by hemispherectomy cases.

2.5 Causal Emergence and Distributed Intelligence

· Causal emergence framework: Formalises when macro-scale variables have causal power not present at the micro-scale. Early work (CE 1.0) used effective information (EI) to compute $\Delta C = EI(M_\phi) - EI(S)$.
· Causal Emergence 2.0: Introduces axiomatic causal primitives — determinism (sufficiency) and specificity (necessity) — combined into causal power $CP = \text{determinism} + \text{specificity} - 1$. These primitives can be apportioned across a multiscale hierarchy to compute unique contributions per scale, leading to a measure of emergent complexity $\mathcal{E}$ as the entropy of normalized unique contributions along causal paths. Recent work advocates averaging over multiple feasible paths to capture full multiscale structure and classify hierarchies (e.g., top-heavy, bottom-heavy, mesoscale-peaked, complex).

2.6 Gaps Addressed by This Research

While the above fields provide building blocks, no existing work combines:

· Online structural plasticity with vector-based capsule routing and dynamic agreement.
· Hamiltonian formalisation of multi-nuclei systems with proven energy bounds and passivity-based stability, including adaptation to structural changes.
· Causal emergence 2.0 quantification of distributed intelligence with path-based apportioning and taxonomy-aware metrics.
· Persistent, event-sourced logging for reproducible experimentation.
· Direct lesion/hemispherectomy experiments to test functional redistribution.

