Chapter 7: Implementation and Evaluation Design

7.1 Implementation in Rust

The system will be implemented in Rust using the following crates:

· nalgebra for matrix/vector operations.
· petgraph for graph representation of the capsule network.
· rusqlite for SQLite persistence with event-sourced logging.
· rayon for parallel capsule evaluation.
· crossbeam for inter-nucleus communication.
· Optional: tch-rs or candle for Graph Transformer layers (if used).

Key design decisions:

· Use petgraph::stable_graph::StableGraph to allow node/edge additions without invalidating indices.
· Event logging with adaptive thresholds based on information-theoretic surprise.
· Serialization of matrices using bincode.

7.2 Persistent State and Reproducibility

The system will log only significant events to avoid overwhelming storage:

· Capsule creation/deletion.
· Highway creation/deletion.
· Weight matrix changes exceeding an adaptive threshold.
· Periodic snapshots (every 1000 steps).

Definition 7.1 (Surprise-Based Logging). For each event type $e$ with observed value $x_t$, maintain rolling mean $\mu_t$ and standard deviation $\sigma_t$. Compute surprise $S_t = |x_t - \mu_t|/\sigma_t$. Log event if $S_t > \tau$ or with probability $p_{\text{sample}}$ if $S_t \leq \tau$.

Theorem 7.1 (Logging Completeness). Assume $x_t$ are i.i.d. from a distribution with finite variance. Then the expected fraction of "informative" events (those with $|x-\mu| > \kappa\sigma$) that are logged is at least $1 - \Phi(\tau) + p_{\text{sample}} \Phi(\tau)$, where $\Phi$ is the CDF of the standardized surprise distribution.

7.3 Evaluation Benchmarks and Metrics

We will evaluate on:

· Continual learning benchmarks: CORe50, Split-CIFAR-100 (using avalanche). Compare against static capsule networks, NEAT, DER++, CODA-P, SMGrNN, and a version of our architecture without Graph Transformer highways.
· Drone network simulation: Simulate a fleet of drones with correlated communication failures (spatial Poisson processes) and resource constraints. Measure task completion rate, mutual information between nuclei, adaptation energy, and causal emergence metrics.
· Lesion/hemispherectomy experiments: After training, randomly remove subsets of capsules (single-nucleus lesions) or entire nuclei (multi-nucleus lesions). Measure recovery time, functional redistribution (via capsule vector similarity pre/post), and changes in CP at macro scales post-reorganization. This directly tests RQ1/RQ2 resilience claims.

Metrics include:

· Resilience Index: $R = \int_{t_0}^{t_1} P(t) dt$ normalized by baseline.
· Adaptation Latency: Time to return to 90% baseline performance after perturbation.
· Functional Redundancy: Minimum number of capsules to remove to degrade performance by X%.
· Resource Efficiency: $\mathcal{R}_w = \frac{P(t_1) - P(t_0)}{\alpha \Delta_{\text{caps}} + \beta \Delta_{\text{syn}} + \gamma \Delta_{\text{comp}} + \epsilon}$.
· Causal Emergence 2.0: CP per scale, unique contributions, emergent complexity $\mathcal{E}$, and taxonomy label.
· Distributed Intelligence: $\mathcal{D} = \bar{\mathcal{E}} + I(N_1; \ldots; N_K)$.

Theorem 7.2 (Bounded Resource Efficiency). Under the assumptions that performance is bounded and each structural change consumes at least $e_{\min}$ energy, and total available energy over the evaluation interval is $E_{\text{total}}$, we have:
\mathcal{R}_w \leq \frac{P_{\max}}{\min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma) \cdot \frac{E_{\text{total}}}{e_{\max}} + \epsilon}.

Proof. Denote $n_{\text{struct}} = \alpha \Delta_{\text{caps}} + \beta \Delta_{\text{syn}} + \gamma \Delta_{\text{comp}}$. Since each change consumes at least $e_{\min}$ energy, $n_{\text{struct}} \cdot e_{\min} \leq E_{\text{total}}$, so $n_{\text{struct}} \leq E_{\text{total}}/e_{\min}$. Then $\min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)(\Delta_{\text{caps}}+\Delta_{\text{syn}}+\Delta_{\text{comp}}) \leq n_{\text{struct}}$, and $\Delta_{\text{caps}}+\Delta_{\text{syn}}+\Delta_{\text{comp}} \geq n_{\text{struct}}/\max(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)$. Combining gives the bound. ∎

7.4 Pre‑registration and Reproducibility

All experiments will be pre‑registered on OSF with a pre‑analysis plan specifying primary outcomes, sample sizes (determined by power analysis on pilot runs), and stopping rules. Docker containers with exact Rust toolchain and dependencies will be provided. A minimal reproducible example (MRE) crate will be released to demonstrate key results.

