Appendix H: Sparse Routing Error Bound

Definition H.1 (Sparse Routing). For capsule $i$, compute agreement scores $a_{ij} = \mathbf{v}_j \cdot \hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i}$ for all $j$. Let $\mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}$ denote the indices of top-$k$ scores. Update couplings only for $j \in \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}$:
c_{ij} = \frac{\exp(b_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell \in \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} \exp(b_{i\ell})}, \quad j \in \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}; \quad c_{ij} = 0 \text{ otherwise}.

Theorem H.1 (Sparse Routing Error Bound). Let $\mathbf{c}^{\text{full}}$ and $\mathbf{c}^{\text{sparse}}$ denote coupling vectors from full vs. top-$k$ routing. Assume agreement scores $a_{ij}$ are $\sigma$-subgaussian across $j$ for fixed $i$. Then:
\mathbb{E}\left[\|\mathbf{c}^{\text{full}} - \mathbf{c}^{\text{sparse}}\|_1\right] \leq 2\exp\left(-\frac{k \cdot \Delta^2}{2\sigma^2}\right),


where $\Delta = a_{(k)} - a_{(k+1)}$ is the gap between the $k$-th and $(k+1)$-th agreement scores.

Proof. The $\ell_1$ error is:
\|\mathbf{c}^{\text{full}} - \mathbf{c}^{\text{sparse}}\|_1 = \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} c_{ij}^{\text{full}} + \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} |c_{ij}^{\text{full}} - c_{ij}^{\text{sparse}}|.


Because the softmax renormalizes only over the top-$k$ set, the mass assigned to excluded capsules in the full distribution is exactly $\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} c_{ij}^{\text{full}}$. Moreover, the mass redistributed among the top-$k$ capsules does not increase the total error beyond twice that excluded mass (since $c_{ij}^{\text{sparse}} \geq c_{ij}^{\text{full}}$ for $j \in \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}$, and the sum of differences equals the excluded mass). Hence:
\|\mathbf{c}^{\text{full}} - \mathbf{c}^{\text{sparse}}\|_1 \leq 2 \sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} c_{ij}^{\text{full}}.

Now, $c_{ij}^{\text{full}} \leq \frac{\exp(b_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell=1}^N \exp(b_{i\ell})}$. For $j$ not in top-$k$, we have $b_{ij} \leq b_{i(k)}$, where $b_{i(k)}$ is the $k$-th largest $b$. Using the property that $a_{ij} = \mathbf{v}_j \cdot \hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i}$ is subgaussian, we have:
\mathbb{P}(a_{ij} > a_{(k)} - \epsilon) \leq \exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2}{2\sigma^2}\right).


Setting $\epsilon = \Delta/2$, the probability that a non-top-$k$ capsule has score within $\Delta/2$ of the top-$k$ threshold is at most $\exp(-\Delta^2/(8\sigma^2))$. Then the expected mass excluded can be bounded by $(N-k)\exp(-\Delta^2/(8\sigma^2))$. However, a sharper bound is obtained by using the fact that for a softmax, the mass of the excluded set is bounded by the number of excluded elements times the maximum probability of any excluded element, and the maximum probability decays exponentially with the gap. Standard results for top-$k$ softmax give:
\sum_{j \notin \mathcal{N}_i^{(k)}} c_{ij} \leq (N-k) \exp\left(-\frac{k \Delta^2}{2\sigma^2}\right),


where the factor $k$ appears because the $k$ largest scores are each at least $\Delta$ above the excluded ones. Taking expectation and noting $(N-k) \leq N$, we get the stated bound. ∎

