Appendix J: Graph Transformer Highways

Definition J.1 (Graph Transformer Highway). Let $\mathbf{U} \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times d}$ be the matrix of capsule output vectors. Multi-head self-attention is defined as:
\text{MultiHead}(\mathbf{U}) = \text{Concat}(\text{head}_1, \ldots, \text{head}_H) \mathbf{W}^O,


\text{head}_h = \text{softmax}\left( \frac{(\mathbf{U} \mathbf{W}_h^Q)(\mathbf{U} \mathbf{W}_h^K)^\top}{\sqrt{d_k}} \right) (\mathbf{U} \mathbf{W}_h^V).


The Graph Transformer layer then computes:
\mathbf{Z} = \text{LayerNorm}\left( \mathbf{U} + \text{MultiHead}(\mathbf{U}) \right),


\mathbf{U}' = \text{LayerNorm}\left( \mathbf{Z} + \text{FFN}(\mathbf{Z}) \right),


where FFN is a two-layer feed-forward network with ReLU activation.

Proposition J.1 (Expressive Capacity). Graph Transformer highways can approximate any permutation-equivariant function on capsule sets to arbitrary precision, given sufficient heads and width.

Proof. This follows from the universal approximation properties of attention mechanisms and the fact that the transformer architecture is a special case of a permutation-equivariant set function. ∎

