Appendix K: Hybrid Generation Trigger with Growth Bounds

Definition K.1 (Hybrid Trigger). For capsule $c$, define:

· Activation mean $\mu_c$ and standard deviation $\sigma_c$ over a rolling window,
· Update variance $\nu_{ic} = \text{var}(\Delta \mathbf{W}_{ic})$ for each incoming highway,
· Global entropy $H_c$ and task correlation $\rho_c$.

Insertion probability:
p_{\text{insert}} = \text{sigmoid}\left( (\sigma_c - \theta_\sigma) + (\theta_\nu - \bar{\nu}_c) + (H_c - \theta_H) - \lambda t \right),


where $\bar{\nu}_c$ is the average of $\nu_{ic}$ over incoming edges, $t$ is network age, and $\lambda > 0$.

Pruning occurs if $\sigma_c < \varepsilon$ and $\bar{\nu}_c < \varepsilon$ for $\varepsilon$ small, with threshold $\theta_{\text{prune}} = \varepsilon + \beta/(1 + \exp(-\gamma(\text{total\_caps} - \text{target\_caps})))$.

Lemma K.1 (Bounded Growth). Under homeostatic scaling (Appendix D) that ensures $\|\mathbf{u}_c\|$ remains bounded, the activation variance $\sigma_c$ is bounded, and update variances $\nu_{ic}$ tend to zero as learning converges. Hence, the expected number of insertions over time is finite and bounded by a geometric series.

Proof. Homeostatic scaling ensures $\|\mathbf{u}_c\| \in [0,1]$, so $\sigma_c \leq 1$ always. As the system approaches a steady state, weight changes become small, so $\nu_{ic} \to 0$. Then $p_{\text{insert}} \to \text{sigmoid}(-\infty) = 0$. Moreover, the decay term $-\lambda t$ ensures that even if local statistics remain slightly above thresholds, the probability decays exponentially with time. The total expected insertions $\sum_{t=0}^\infty p_{\text{insert}}(t)$ is bounded by a geometric series, hence finite. ∎

